The lengthening and shortening of vowels in other cases in Homer and Virgil—we mean the cases in which the shortening of a vowel long by position is not involved—can all be satisfactorily explained without the accent, viz„ in Arsis and Thesis. In Virgil the Arsis is scarcely ever under the word accent, and vowels are shortened by that poet, and in Homer in hiatus.
